                    <!-- <center>   <img src="{% static "img/hydrogen_series0.png" %}" width="500"></center><br><br> -->
                    Each element in nature have a characteristic spectral emmision decomposition, which is used as a ``fingerprint'' that allow us to determine the chemical content of many substances. This is for example, how we deduce the elemtary content of starts, galaxies, cosmic dust, etc.<br><br> 
		    <h2>Quick Review of Spherical Coordinates: Continuation</h2>
		  The transformation from spherical coordinates to Cartesian coordinates is given by the relations: 

		 $$x = r\,\sin\theta\cos\phi\,\quad y = r\,\sin\theta\sin\phi\,\quad  z = r\,\cos\phi\,.$$



<iframe id="embed-iframe" allowTransparency="true" allow="encrypted-media *" allowfullscreen height="615" width="660" border="0" scrolling="no" frameborder="0" marginwheight="0" marginwidth="0" src="https://app.jove.com/embed/player?id=14691&access=151aa96972&t=1&s=1&fpv=1"></iframe>
<br><br>
Let me run some few basic questions <a href="https://questioncreator.iclicker.com/questions/sets" target="_blank"> on the iClicker cloud app. </a>

                    <center>   <img src="{% static "img/spherical0.png" %}" width="500"></center>
Consider the reference frame indicated on the blackboard. The blackboard is in the $y-z$ plane, $x$ is coming out of the backboard towards you. Approximately, which of the following vectors in spherical coordinates is pointing to my head?

			<ol  style="line-height:300%" type="A">
		   <img src="{% static "img/iclicker.png" %}" width="100"> <br>
		 <!-- longer -->
		   <li> $(r,\theta,\phi)=(2\, {\rm meters}, \pi/2,\pi/4)$</li>
		   <li> $(r,\theta,\phi)=(-2\, {\rm meters}, \pi/2,7\pi/4)$</li>
		    <li> $(r,\theta,\phi)=(2\, {\rm meters}, -\pi/4,\pi/2)$</li>

		 <li> None of the above </li>
				</ol>
	<br><br>
		    
	A usual and ilustrative way of representing functions of the polar angle are polar plots, which are the usual way of representing probabilities for the electron in an atom. A polar plot is a plot of a function $\rho=f(\theta)$ in polar coordinates,
                    <center>   <img src="{% static "img/polar-coordinates.png" %}" width="300"></center><br>
	Think about a unit-circle in polar coordinates (say the outer circle in figure above). It corresponds to the which function in polar coordinates?  
			<ol  style="line-height:300%" type="A">
		   <img src="{% static "img/iclicker.png" %}" width="100"> <br>
		 <!-- longer -->
		   <li> $\rho(\theta)=\cos(\theta) $</li>
		   <li> $\rho(\theta)=\sin(\theta) $</li>
		    <li> $\rho(\theta)=1 $</li>
		    <li> None of the above</li>

				</ol>
	<br><br>
Can you plot the cardioid: $\rho(\theta)=1-\cos(\theta)$?______ (yes, no)<br>
		    <h2> Schrodinger Equation in Spherical Coordinates</h2>
		    
                    For the Schrodinger equation we need the operator,
                    \begin{equation}
                    \nabla^2={1\over r^2}\left[{\partial\over \partial r}\left(r^2{\partial\over \partial r}\right)+{1\over {\rm sin}(\theta)}{\partial\over \partial\theta}\left({\rm sin}(\theta){\partial\over\partial\theta}\right)  +{1\over {\rm sin}^2(\theta)}{\partial^2\over \partial\phi^2}\right]
                    \end{equation}
                    In order to compute probabilities, we will also need the <em>Integration measure</em>,
                    \begin{equation}
                   \boxed{ dV=r^2 \,{\rm sin\theta}\,d\theta\,\phi\, dr}
                    \end{equation}
                    3D Schrodinger equation takes the form,
                    \begin{equation}
                    -{\hbar^2\over 2 m}{1\over r^2}\left[{\partial\over \partial r}\left(r^2{\partial\over \partial r}\right)+{1\over {\rm sin}(\theta)}{\partial\over \partial\theta}\left({\rm sin}(\theta){\partial\over\partial\theta}\right)  +{1\over {\rm sin}^2(\theta)}{\partial^2\over \partial\phi^2}\right]\psi(r,\theta,\phi)+U(r)\psi(r,\theta,\phi)=E\psi(r,\theta,\phi)
                    \end{equation}
		                       
                    With potential energy given by,
                    \begin{equation}
                    U(r)=-{1\over4\pi \epsilon_0}{e^2\over r}\,
                    \end{equation}

                    In order to solve this large equation, we will use our  old separation of variables method,
                    \begin{equation}
                    \psi(r,\theta,\phi)=R(r)\Theta(\theta)\Phi(\phi)\,,
                    \end{equation}
                    which lead us to the following independent differential equations,
                    <br><br>
                    The <b> radial</b> equation:
                    $$-{\partial\over \partial r}\left(r^2{\partial\over \partial r}\right)R(r)-{2mr^2\over \hbar^2}(E-U(r))R(r)=C\,R(r)$$
                    <hr>
                    The <b> polar</b> equation:
                    $$ {\rm sin}(\theta){\partial\over \partial\theta}\left({\rm sin}(\theta){\partial\over\partial\theta}\right)\Theta(\theta)  -C\,{\rm sin}^2(\theta)=D\Theta(\theta)$$
                    <hr>
                    The <b> azimuthal</b> equation:
                    $$ {\partial^2\Phi(\phi)\over \partial\phi^2}=-D\Phi(\phi)$$
                    <hr>
                    <h3>The Azimuthal equation</h3>
                    Let's start with the simplest of them all, the most generic solution to the azimuthal equation is given by,
                    $ {\partial^2\Phi(\phi)\over \partial\phi^2}=-D\Phi(\phi)$ 

			<ol  style="line-height:300%" type="A">
		   <img src="{% static "img/iclicker.png" %}" width="100"> <br>
		 <!-- longer -->
		   <li> $\Phi(\phi)=A e^{+\sqrt{D}\phi}+B e^{-\sqrt{D}\phi} $</li>
		   <li> $\Phi(\phi)=A e^{+i\sqrt{D}\phi}+B e^{-i\sqrt{D}\phi} $</li>
		   <li>$\Phi(\phi)=A e^{+i\sqrt{D}\phi}$</li>
		    <li> $\Phi(\phi)=A e^{-i\sqrt{D}\phi}$</li>

		 <li> None of the above </li>
				</ol>
			<br><br>
			As we have seen previously, the most general solutions of such equation is,
			$$\Phi(\phi)=A e^{+i\sqrt{D}\phi}+B e^{-i\sqrt{D}\phi}\,. $$ 
        Now we need to impose boundary conditions. Notice that this is a plane-wave moving clock-wise plus a plane-wave moving in the oposite way. Why can be wrong with this picture?

<br><br>
	
	Notice that we don't a boundary or a potential "barrier" in this direction that will bounce the wavefuntion, so we can only have a wave moving in either direction. Let us pick up: $$\Phi(\phi)=A e^{+i\sqrt{D}\phi}$$
Imposing continuity of the wavefunction, it needs to satisfy $$\Phi(0)=\Phi(2\pi)\,, $$
What does imply?
			<ol  style="line-height:300%" type="A">
		   <img src="{% static "img/iclicker.png" %}" width="100"> <br>
		 <!-- longer -->
		   <li> $A=1 $</li>
		   <li> $D= m $ with $m$ an integer</li>
		   <li> $D= m^2 $ with $m$ an integer</li>
		   <li> $D = m/2 $ with $m$ an integer</li>
		    <li> $D= (m/2)^2 $ with $m$ an integer</li>

				</ol>
			<br><br>



			Or more explicitly, $$\Phi(\phi)=A e^{i m_{\ell}\,\phi}$$ with $m_{\ell}=0, \pm 1, \pm 2,\cdots$. The meaning of the sublabel $\ell$  is coming up.
			             <center>   <img src="{% static "img/phi_standing_wave.png" %}" width="500"></center>

                    <h3>The Polar equation</h3>
                    The polar equation is a challenging equation, but perhaps we have some intuition on what can of functions will be the building blocks. Also, since the polar coordinate is also an angle, boundary conditions will tell us that the constant $C$ should be related to some integer quantity. It turns out that to be,
                    $$C=-\ell(\ell+1) $$
		    <!-- $$\sqrt{D}= \boxed{ m_{\ell}=0,\pm 1, \pm 2,\cdots,\pm\ell\,}.$$ -->
                    This has to do with the fact that the combined polar and azimuthal equations are the square of the angular momentum operator, and which is quantized by the integer $\ell$, whereas the integer $m_{\ell}$ corresponds to the quantization of projection of angular momenta in the $z$ direction:<br><br> <center> $ \boxed{L_z=\hbar m_{\ell}} $ and $ \boxed{|L|=\hbar\sqrt{\ell(\ell+1)}}$.</center>
                    <br>
                    <em>Remember that the angular momentum $L={\bf p}\times {\bf r}$  is a vector perpendicular to the orbital plane</em><br><br>
                    <center>   <img src="{% static "img/spin_quant0.png" %}" width="500"></center>
                    <br>
                    What about the classical limit?<br><br>
                    After some algebra, we can rewrite the polar equation in the form,
                    $$                   (1+x^2){\partial\Theta(x)\over \partial x^2}-2 x { \partial\Theta(x)\over  \partial x}+\ell(\ell+1)\Theta(x)-{m_{x}^2\over (1-x^2)}\Theta(x)$$ with $x={\rm cos}(\theta)$.
                    This equation is known in the mathematical literature as the                         <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Associated_Legendre_polynomials">associated Legendre equation</a>, which defined the associated Legendre polynomials.<br><br>

                    The combine solutions $\Theta_{\ell, m_{\ell}}\Phi_{m_{\ell}}$ are known as the <b>spherical harmonics</b>
                    <center>   <img src="{% static "img/spherical_harm0.png" %}" width="800"></center><br>
                    <h3>Angular probabilities</h3>
                    Even though we are considering a system with spherical symmetry, and at a given angular momentum $\ell$ the total probability would be angular independent, as it should be for a spherical symmetric system, it is important to have understand the angular dependence in order to gain a better understanding of the total wavefunction (among other things, in practical experiments, we are able to distinguish diferent angular components, by sort of breaking the spherical symmetry by applying an interaction).
                    <center>   <img src="{% static "img/angular_prob1_0.png" %}" width="350"> <img src="{% static "img/angular_prob2_0.png" %}" width="370"></center>

		    <h2>Next: "Radial solutions for the Hydrogen atom.</h2>
